      },
      "hypothesis": "In the stressed bear regime, 21-day momentum continuation (effectively short-side) persists because forced deleveraging dominates order flow: elevated credit spreads, a strong dollar bid, a flat curve, and heavy volume mark absorption failure rather than rotation, so intermediate-horizon downside momentum continues instead of mean-reverting. The 21-day lookback is deliberately shorter than the regime-defining roc_63 window; the meta-learner, fed exogenous credit/dollar stress features, screens out exhausted-move entries and the sparse counter-trend longs via the ev_breakeven threshold.",
      "causal_story": "In this regime, forced deleveraging is the dominant flow: credit spreads are elevated (cs_spread_21 median_q 0.584, IQR up to 0.88), the dollar bid is strong (dxy_z252 0.558), the curve is flat (us_5y2y_z252 0.304 lower), and participation is heavy (volume 0.700 higher). When liquidity providers demand wider credit compensation while volume runs hot, selling is absorption-failure rather than rotation, so intermediate-horizon downside momentum continues rather than mean-reverts - consistent with bollinger_meanrev's LOWER hit rate here versus momentum_zscore's HIGHER hit rate. The edge: 21-day momentum, filtered by exogenous credit/dollar stress rather than price alone, captures the fat left tail (return IQR 0.162-0.835).",
      "feature_overrides": {
        "add": [
          "cs_spread_21",
          "dxy_z252",
          "us_5y2y_z252",
          "vix_chg_5",
          "volume"
        ],
        "drop": []
      },
